<div class="reflist">
<div class="mw-references-wrap"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-16"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Initially described as a killer, Jara gave life to the prince <a href="/wiki/Jarasandha" title="Jarasandha">Jarasandha</a> of <a href="/wiki/Magadha" title="Magadha">Magadha</a> and was then adored as the saviour of children throughout the kingdom.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-17"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Initially a devourer of children, Hariti was transformed by the <a href="/wiki/Buddha" class="mw-redirect" title="Buddha">Buddha</a> into their protector. In contemporary iconography, Hariti, like Shashthi, is pictured surrounded with children and is affiliated with a cat.</span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>
